The Washington Post's investigation revealed wounded soldiers left forgotten at Walter Reed due to bureaucratic failures.
President George W. Bush's commitment to veterans was emphasized amid calls for improved care standards.
The Defense Department vowed to address neglect in military hospitals, with Obama and Senator McCaskill proposing legislation for oversight and accountability.
Defense Secretary Gates promised swift action and accountability for the deplorable conditions.
Reports of bureaucratic indifference and poor living conditions sparked outrage, prompting urgent reforms and a commitment to prioritize wounded soldiers' care.
Gates' pledge to hold officials responsible and improve care standards underscored the need for immediate action.
